Today marks a “last”…

We all remember “firsts”… but the “lasts” make us stop and think… like the last day you were with your friends before you went off to college… or the last day you lived at a certain address… those things kind of hit differently. 

I should be jumping for joy… for more than 35 years this has been a part of my life… it has set the pattern for Sunday. All of those early Monday mornings heading to school when I was a teacher in my 20s… the crack of dawn Monday morning conference calls, before long days in sales when I was a Corporate girl in my 30s and into my 40s… then for the last decade… starting my Monday mornings with my clients as an Aesthetician and business owner… my Sundays have always revolved around a strong start to the week, planning, prepping, packing… so I could be out the door early every Monday morning… for as long as I can remember. 

Today is my last Monday morning. It may not sound like a big thing for some people… but when it has been the pattern, the habit of your life for almost 4 decades… it feels really strange! 

This is my last week to work in 2022… and when I come back in February of 2023… I am scaling back a bit, which means a shorter work week that doesn’t start on Monday. 

There’s a time for everything… and it’s time for me to slow down. I’m not going anywhere… as a matter of fact there will be some new, fun things to come in 2023! But, as for my time to be racing around on Sunday, to hit it hard on Monday… this is the last one. 

My last Monday… let me repeat that for myself… 

My. Last. Monday. 

Thanks for sharing it with me!! ♥️♥️♥️

Let’s make it a good one!

L A S H E S …. They can make us look awake and polished when we don’t want to do anything else! 

The problem… like most things, as we age… they lose their luster, thin out, and break off. 

So… here are my tricks for keeping my lashes long and healthy, and might I say… perky!😉

• A lash serum is essential for length and fullness. I have used Latisse by Allergan for years! Why? It is the only lash serum that is FDA approved, and IT WORKS! Here’s the trick…. If you are a newbie, you need to use the serum every night for 3 months. (The equivalent of a full bottle) By then you will see a LOT of growth, so you can titrate back to every 2-3 nights. I have done this for over a decade. It’s quick, easy, and safe.

• Next, you MUST keep your lashes conditioned! My go to is Aquaphor… yes, Aquaphor… (I use it for a lot of things) After I apply my lash serum, I run a little of the Aquaphor through my lashes. It keeps them so soft and conditioned. 

• Don’t wear waterproof mascara!! It is so hard on your lashes and takes too much effort to remove. If your mascara doesn’t come off with your cleanser, it’s too much. My all time fave mascara is @byterryofficial Growth Booster.

• Lastly, the game changer… once your lashes are healthy and have length… a *lash lift and tint* takes it to the NEXT LEVEL. The trick here, is finding someone who knows what they are doing! It can be the best service, or it can be a disaster! I am fortunate to have Kayla @thebeautybabenash on board. She has perfected this service over the years! I get mine done every 2-3 months. If it’s done correctly, it will last that long! 

I am asked quite often if I have lash extensions… nope… I just give my natural lashes a little extra love! I hope this helps… and remember, have patience with the process.♥️

What a month can do………….

When I decided last fall that I was going to take a sabbatical In January, I had no idea how it would effect me. I knew I was burned out, it happens to all of us relative to our paradigm, but in my case, it was just something that I would normally push through. 

If you know me, you know, I have two speeds. Full throttle… or crashed. The first is 90% of the time. It’s how I have always been. Has it been great for careers? Yep. Has it been good for my personal life, mentally, physically and spiritually? Nope.

I think it took the crazy emergency surgery scare in November to solidify that I needed to stop everything for a month. Literally STOP. What a foreign thought for me. I have been full throttle since I started my first career, 35 years ago. In a bazaar way… I became addicted to stress. It fueled me to do more.

This month has been filled with every possible emotion one could imagine. I have felt everything from… complete restlessness … to getting a glimpse of what retirement might look like. I have had to take a good hard look at what my priorities are, and what they aren’t. What matters in life, and what doesn’t. What I am capable of, and what I’m just not. What I want for the remainder of my years, and what I don’t. Who I am, and who I am not. 

Most of all… I am focusing on the treasures. The smallest, to the most incredible blessings that I have been gifted by God. I have lived much longer than I have left, and I need to make it count. I need to parlay those gifts into the new fuel that drives me, knowing that time is a commodity that is precious, and comes with no guarantee.

Maybe the big scare happened for a reason. Maybe it was God’s way of opening my eyes, and forcing me to face myself. This month was the antithesis of what I had imagined. It was so much more. It was needed and it just may have changed my life. 

#life #learn #lessons #time #change #fiftysomething

🔸 Chemicals, Toxins, and Skincare🔸

There are S U C H misconceptions around what ingredients should and shouldn’t be in the skincare products that we use. This is where I encourage you not to jump on any bandwagon that sounds good, and rather make yourself informed.

When it comes to chemicals… remember, scientifically speaking… everything has chemical matter, ie. water and air. Clearly we don’t want our body’s largest organ to be penetrated by toxic chemicals. Then comes the “toxic” ingredient discussion… which is another one that gets completely misconstrued. Often what we are eating or even breathing can be more toxic, tenfold, over topical ingredients. Does that mean that our skincare needs to be comprised of only botanicals and supposedly “all natural”-“clean” ingredients? (More buzz words that are overused without full understanding.) The answer is NO!! 
This is where you need to become aware of which specific #ingredients, #additives, and #preservatives should be avoided. There is nothing wrong with “Medical Grade” skincare, as long as the following 5 are not in the list of ingredients:

1. Fragrance- The smell may be nice, but it is most likely a cause for sensitizing or irritation of the skin. 
2. Propylene Glycol- A chemical additive used in food and cosmetics as a stabilizer, emulsifier or humectant, which can be harmful to the moisture barrier of your skin, over time, causing dryness, irritation and the inability to retain moisture.
3. Kathon- (methylchlorothiazolinone) A preservative that can be sensitizing to the skin and/or cause contact dermatitis.
4. Sodium Lauryl Sulfate- An additive in cleansing products used to allow them to foam. In studies, it has been linked to skin irritation, neurotoxicity, cancer and endocrine disruption.
5. Parabens- There are a long list of parabens, with the role of being a preservative, that allows your products to survive months or even years on the shelves. Parabens can mimic hormones in the body and disrupt functions of the endocrine system... along with reports that they have been linked to breast cancer. (Methlyparaben, ethylparaben, propylparaben and butylparaben) .

#beinformed #ingredients #skincare

💦 The skinny on Cleansing 💦

Is it important to cleanse your face
 AM and PM? 

The answer is YES! 

Here are some tips on cleansing………….

The best way to allow for your skincare routine to work, is to start on skin that is clean and balanced. 

Let’s start with PM, because that’s the cleanse that is the most important. 
2-3 cleanses are necessary. The first cleanse is to remove the makeup. The second cleanse is to clean the face, deep into the pores. If you see that the water in the sink is still not clear when you splash, then a third cleanse is necessary. 
Using a washcloth is fine, only if gently used… no scrubbing. Once the face is clean, you are ready for your PM skincare routine, and those restorative hours when your skincare products are really doing their job.

The AM cleanse IS necessary. Yes, you went to bed with a clean face, but odds are you applied some type of skincare before you went to sleep. There is always some type of residue left in the morning. So, the same rule applies. You want a clean face with a balanced Ph, so that your skin is ready for your AM routine, no matter how simple it may be. 

Remember, even if you don’t wear makeup, and you have the most minimal skincare routine, your skin still produces oils, and accumulates dead skin. Both of which can clog pores, ultimately making them larger. 

So START and END your day with a clean pallet. You will get the most out of your skincare products, and your pores will thank you!

To say that I had to jump into “womanhood” early is an understatement. Here’s my story. 
(Part One) 

I’ve been quite open about having a hysterectomy at a very early age, and navigating the world of HRT just as long, 27 years. But how I got there, and how I managed being thrust into such an adult scenario, is the rest of the story. Why do I tell it? Because not everyone has the usual progression of the reproductive years- peri- menopause- and post menopause. I am one of those women. 

When I was in my teens, my cycle was brutal from the get go. I knew once a month, I would be in terrible pain, and would have to deal with the fear of extreme embarrassment, as a competitive athlete who was in team shorts or a cheerleading skirt, year round. I was the poster child for PMS. The older I got the worse it got, until my first trip to a GYN when I was 17. I was started on birth control to try to ease my cycle, but it didn’t help. By the time I was in my early 20s it was so bad, it was starting to effect other aspects of my health. 
My GYN suspected endometriosis, but the only way to find out was diagnostic surgery. 
I was 22 when I had my first first laparoscopy, and little did I know then… I would spend the next 8 years in and out of the OR. As he expected, I had endometriosis. It was all cauterized, and then the waiting game… well, it didn’t take long before I was right back in the same boat. I had the same surgery at 24, then again at 26 to remove the evil webbing… but still no relief. At this point it was made clear to me that having children wouldn’t be likely. 
As my situation continued to worsen, my GYN suspected fibroid tumors. Ultrasounds proved him right. The next surgery was a Myomectomy. I was 28. This entailed a full bilateral cut, literally cleaning me out, tumors, and more endometriosis, then a 6 week recovery. Then his strategy was to put me on Lupron injections for a year, to keep anything from growing back. It was basically menopause. At 28, I was hot flashing and God knows what… but for the first time… I didn’t have a cycle, I didn’t have pain, and this monthly injection allowed me to feel great! 
(Next post)

My journey (Part Two) 

So Lupron, which literally halted my ovaries from working (the source of the endometriosis) was my lucky charm! … until I had to stop it one year later. Then…the inevitable happened…my misery returned with a vengeance! 
At this point, I WAS DONE!! I had spent the better part of my 20s like some kind of reproductive lab rat… and I wanted out!!
I was 29 years old, and the only other option was a hysterectomy. Remember, this was almost 30 years ago… women my age rarely had hysterectomies. It was a big deal. And in my case it would mean ovaries, uterus, and cervix. I didn’t care… I was so over it… and just wanted to get on with living. My GYN was hesitant, but agreed. At that… he made me wait a few months, to be sure. 
At 30, I had a full hysterectomy. The same bilateral cut, just a different outcome. I was told about HRT, but was so young and so spent, that I didn’t think too much about it, and I was started on it the day after my surgery. After another 6 week recovery, I settled into a really healthy life! No pain, and no more surgery to plan… and I felt great!! For the next 23 years, I had a new lease on life. I was Wonder Woman! And in hindsight, I think I took it for granted. I thought that it would be forever… until 5 years ago, at 52 when it all fell through the floor. (Just after these pics were taken) I had an extremely stressful run, and it took a toll on my body, and everything that was working so smoothly, suddenly took a 180. Crazy things were happening to my body, out of the blue. So, it was time for a change in HRT and a new overall health approach, by way of Integrative Medicine. The last few years have been a journey to say the least, but I have learned to accept that what worked for me “then” was bound to change. I also learned that my Wonder Woman mentality wasn’t the healthiest after all, and maybe this was God’s grace in action. Either way, at 57, I am doing well, and have a new understanding of where I am in life, physically and mentally. I have learned a lot, and hope my sharing, helps someone else. Our health path is a journey ladies… and… it ain’t easy being a woman!😉 #menopause #hormones #womenshealth #life

W H Y  W E I G H T S ??? 
Even at 57?  Even really heavy ones? 

There is such a misconception that weights are going to bulk you up. They won’t. There is also a misconception that if your back hurts you don’t need to lift weights. Also wrong. I have chronic back pain, and the main reason why? Because my back is weak. Weight training, properly, has helped my back immensely! 

What will weights do for you? F A C T S :

• You will burn more calories. Yes, cardio burns calories during the session, but it takes more energy (calories) for your body to maintain muscle than it does fat. So by lifting weights and adding lean muscle mass, you’ll boost your metabolism and turn your body into a fat burning machine.

Can you shrink your pores?? 

The operative word here is “shrink” or actually make them smaller. And… unfortunately the answer is no. However, there is hope, because you can minimize the appearance of your pores… or “refine” them. 

So, why do our pores get larger? This usually happens with age. Sometimes it is hereditary. However, the most common culprits consist of anything that allows them to accumulate oil or debris, such as heavy occlusive creams or makeup, worst of all, sleeping in makeup. That’s a pore clogger and expander for sure, especially if done repeatedly. For some, it is simply the over production of oil.

So, what can we do to minimize the appearance of our pores? 

1) keep them clean
2) boost collagen and elastin

And, how do we do that? 

• Use non-occlusive products and makeup
• Cleanse your face 2 times a day
• Use a Retinol- cell turnover and collagen production 
• Treat breakouts- reduce oil
• Wear sunscreen- avoid collagen loss
• Exfoliate manual/ chemical 
• Microneedling- boost collagen 
• Chemical peels- reduce sebum
• Laser- exfoliation and collagen production

So, the take away is to keep the pores from becoming filled to begin. Use products that will help to keep the pores clean, hence refined, and use products, or seek procedures that help to boost collagen, allowing for a more plumped, smooth appearance. So… you can’t physically make pores smaller, but you sure can refine them!

Insomnia S U C K S !! 
But… did you know this???🌞

….the sun can help it. I knew that being outside and moving was good… but honestly, I didn’t know exactly what being in the sun had to do with getting a better nights sleep. 

🌞Sunshine plays a role in regulating hormones and sleep patterns by affecting the melatonin circadian rhythm.🌞

Melatonin is a hormone created by the pineal gland in the brain that is released into the bloodstream. Darkness prompts the pineal gland to start producing melatonin, while light causes it to stop. As a result, melatonin helps regulate the circadian rhythm to synchronize the sleep-wake cycle.

So… as soon as you rise in the morning, look for the sun. Step outside and soak in the light. It synchronizes your body clock with the 24 hour day, and signals to your brain to stop making melatonin. One study suggests, when the sun is up, get as much sunlight as you can… and when the sun is down, keep it dark. 

Now Circadian Rhythm makes more sense! 

Maybe this is why, during my bouts of insomnia, my body craves exercising outside? 

And… maybe this is why people in warmer climates seem to live healthier lives?

Who knows… regardless… get outside… (wear your sunscreen😉) but when you can… soak up the sun!🌞

What I remember most is what happened the days, weeks and months AFTER that tragic day.

We all remember where we were when it unfolded, but like most, we were paralyzed by the horrific events. I was supposed to fly across the country that day for a Pharmaceutical launch, along with thousands of other reps who worked for GSK. Most of our flights were grounded. Our jobs, at that point, were to call our co-workers to account for everyone. The launch never happened. I spent 24 hours in front of the TV crying in disbelief, watching the footage over and over, and waiting for updates. For those of us who were adults at the time, that day was a total blur… a horrible dream. 

But what I remember the most was what happened afterwards. I didn’t work the next day… like many… it wasn’t important. What was important was the literal rally of all that was good. Family members, friends, neighbors, people from all walks of life… were in this together. 

American flags were flown everywhere! Businesses, schools, churches, homes… cloaked in red, white and blue. Then cars… every day, more and more cars, flying the flag proudly. You couldn’t buy a flag anywhere… sold out!🇺🇸 

From the depths of tragedy we saw the best in humanity. As bad as the news continued to unfold, in the search for those unaccounted… hope became stronger, and people came together. I will never forget it. The pride for the USA was fierce. 

That was 22 years ago. 

I will never forget that day… 9/11… but just as much… I will never forget the days and weeks afterwards. United We Stand never felt so real. 🇺🇸

The double whammy…
This week got me…and my attitude took a deep dive. My back issues, that I’ve had for decades, and fibromyalgia, which I’ve also battled since my 30s, decided to invade me at the same time. I didn’t handle it with grace.

I never talk about fibromyalgia, because there are so many misconceptions about it… and too many people just think it’s aches and pains… it’s not. I first experienced it when I was in my 30s. I was in Pharma sales at the time, and can remember thinking I had arthritis. It always starts in my hands. 2 Rheumatologists later… No arthritis… but rather fibromyalgia. It’s different for everyone. Mine starts in my extremities, then my whole body… bones, joints, muscles… everything aches and throbs. Then comes the fatigue. 

Over the years, I have had flare ups… they usually last about 2-3 days… then I am free of it for months. I will literally forget about it. There have been years that I have only had flare ups once or twice. I have learned how to work through them. But I know my limits. As I have aged… I have flare ups more frequently. 

Then the old back… it’s been a problem for as long as I can remember. Being a young athlete, spending 15 years of my career on the road, then the last 12 as an Aesthetician, mixed with high intensity workouts… have created the perfect storm. Like my fibromyalgia, it comes in waves. 

The last 2 weeks… it has been the wrath of both. Hence, I have been quite MIA. 

I am finally getting some relief in both areas… but man… let me tell ya… the combo was a beast! And so was my mindset. If you know me, you know I don’t do well at all if I’m not “going and doing and being productive”… and I’m not cool at all if I can’t exercise. That is my therapy! 

I’m coming around and so is my attitude. God bless @blueeyedpilot ♥️ What a freakin SAINT! And thanks to my team for covering all of the bases for me… and my sweet clients for understanding. 

Life is one big lesson… and aging ain’t for the weak!! And as I always try to remind myself…
This too shall pass.♥️

See ya soon!

Can you step away from Social Media? 

I grew up in an era when there was
no technology. Imagine if you will… You had a TV with 4 channels and a phone on the wall. No answering machine, just a “busy signal” or an endless ring if you weren’t home. My mom took the phone off of the hook at meal time, because that was family time. 
There were no devices. There was no email, no texting, no apps, social media, stress about likes, views or content, no rabbit hole scrolling. Everything was left to the imagination. There was zero pressure to keep up… once you walked away in person. You had time to clear your mind. 
We played outside and used our creative minds, rather than staying indoors with a screen. I truly feel like times were much more simple. Mental health was rarely ever a topic.
If you had an appointment, you wrote in a calendar, and you just showed up. There were no appointment reminders. You went to school, and if you needed something from your parent, you went to the office to ask permission to use the phone. You saw your friends at school, church, and after school activities, then… you were with your family. I truly crave these times again. Being born in the 60s, sometimes I want to go back. 
Yes… I agree, progressive times have had a lot of advantages. I truly acknowledge that Social Media has played a huge role in the success of my business. But what I also know…. this past weekend without it… gave me a lot more free time to live in the actual present… and man, it was good. Try to step away from it for a while… Can you?? I promise it will be there when you get back.

Do you believe that your whole life can change in a day? I do… because mine did…
October 26th, 2019.

Life is funny… it waits until you aren’t expecting anything… and then BAM! 

If you’ve been around here for a while, you know the story. October 26th, 2019 was the date of my 35th High School Reunion. I had been to all of my BA reunions, and wasn’t too jazzed about going to this one. It was pouring rain, I was cozied up with Nash watching football, and my texts were blowing up… one by one, my girlfriends were bailing on the reunion. I had pretty much decided this would be the one that I would miss.

Why I changed my mind? I don’t really know… but I threw myself together in record timing and headed out in the rain. I figured I would pop in, say Hi, make the rounds, then slip out. 
Little did I know…

I was in a really good place… or so I thought… I guess it’s true, you don’t know what you don’t know. It was the week before my 54th birthday, I had a great career, a circle of wonderful friends, I had my health, and was quite content. 

Then, on October 26th, 2019… in a matter of 2 hours… the most incredible human turned my world inside out… in the very best way. That night, my now husband, whom I’ve known since I was 10… approached me at the reunion and told me he had loved me since the day we met, when we were 10 years old. We had gone our separate ways over the years, but he could never shake the way he felt about me. This person, who I always considered to be one of the kindest, and most solid people… and I never knew… all those years, the way he felt. From that night on, we have been inseparable. He has changed my life in the most unimaginable ways… this prince… and this fairytale… and this life that is now mine… all started on that rainy night, at that 35th High School reunion, on October 26th, 2019. ♥️

November 15th… I can’t believe it’s been a year! 
In the first picture I am laughing and saying good night to Jeff. He was on a trip and would be home the next day. In the second picture, less than 24 hours later I am heading into emergency surgery. This only reminds me that ✨We truly don’t know what tomorrow holds✨

Little did I know when I went to bed that night, that I would wake up about 2 hours later in the most excruciating pain I have EVER experienced. I had no idea what was happening. I literally felt like I was going to explode. I ended up in the ER an hour later (thanks to a sweet neighbor) to find out, after scans, that I had a bowel blockage and my stomach was completely filled. An NG tube was put in (the worst!) to drain my stomach, then I was admitted. The hope was that the blockage would relieve itself. I continued to get worse, and more scans revealed that I had adhesions from previous surgeries wrapped around my intestines causing the blockage. At that point I was taken directly into surgery. 

I was fortunate. The surgery was successful. Had we waited much longer, it could have been a very different scenario. I was in the hospital for several days, and came home to a slow recovery. 

That experience gave me a very different outlook on life. When I look at those pictures, I think… wow… if only I had known what was about to happen. 

So… I STRESS this… we are not invincible. We are not promised tomorrow. We have no control over unforeseen circumstances. 

Every day… even the crappy ones, are gifts. 

Remember that.

If you watched my stories on Saturday, I was asking for your input on my “filmy” hair situation. My hair feels almost like it has lotion in it, even right after washing. It has been this way for a while. I have tried detox/clarifying shampoos, to remove any possible build up. I don’t use a lot of product. I have washed it in both a filtered shower and one without. I have changed nothing about my diet or any meds/supplements that I take. 

So I shared it with you in hopes to solve the mystery. Quite a few of you have experienced the same thing… and I got a lot of suggestions, most of which I had tried… except for this one…

Baking Soda and Apple Cider Vinegar. I was a little skeptical at first, but I gave it a whirl. I got my hair completely wet, and used a mixture of baking soda and water, about half and half, that I had mixed into a paste. I worked it through my hair, giving the scalp a good scrub. Then I rinsed. I was quite surprised at how good it felt in the shower.(not really sure what I was expecting) Then I washed it out with a very gentle shampoo. Then came the Vinegar rinse. Again, this was about half and half, mixed with water. It actually felt weird. My wet hair kind of felt like it could have been super dry… so I followed up with a rich conditioner. (I wish you could have seen the menagerie of a science experiment on the shower floor!) Then I rinsed really well, for fear of ending up with the same “over condtioned” feeling hair.

It brushed out easily without any detangler. I used a little bit of mousse for volume… I mean a tad… then just did a rough dry. (Me and the round brush don’t get along!)

So… it definitely has a LOT more bounce and volume, and is much brighter. The only mistake I think I made was the amount of conditioner that I used… But overall, for now, it feels better. Let’s see how it feels tomorrow.

Yes… this is a First World Problem for sure!! But it has had me perplexed … so I called on you! Thanks for all of your DMs and suggestions! I hope this helps some of you! (One other thing I am going to do is get new brushes and test the ph of our water!💦)

I will keep you posted friends. ♥️ #hair
